{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503352"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:59:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:59:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2021"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2021"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.61,0.01,0.12,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114342"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2021"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2282"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8085"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47828"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114342"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with shortness of breath. She is 37 weeks pregnant with her second child. Her first pregnancy was uncomplicated with a spontaneous vaginal delivery of a healthy boy, who is now two years old. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has been on maternity leave for three weeks. This morning she developed sudden onset shortness of breath, which is unusual as she has been active throughout her pregnancy. She has pain in her right axilla on inspiration and feels lightheaded. She has a known hypersensitivity reaction to iodine-containing contrast material.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Heart sounds are dual with no added sounds. There is equal air entry bilaterally with no added sounds. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. She has bilateral ankle oedema but the calves are soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECG shows sinus tachycardia at 110/min with no ST changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELower limb doppler ultrasound was performed and did not reveal a DVT. Chest XR was normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform coagulation studies and D-dimer","Arrange V/Q scan","Therapeutic dose rivaroxaban","Arrange CT pulmonary angiography","Commence enoxaparin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary embolism (PE) in pregnancy is a difficult diagnosis. Patients may present with dyspnoea, tachycardia and leg swelling which can be normal physiological changes of pregnancy or pathological signs of PE. PE is the most likely diagnosis considering her presentation with acute onset shortness of breath, pleuritic chest pain, light-headedness and sinus tachycardia. Oxygen saturations can remain normal and clinical evidence of deep vein thrombosis may not always be present. A judgement must be made as to whether to give empirical anticoagulants before confirming the diagnosis or wait until investigations have been performed. In this instance, as the patient is haemodynamically stable and there will be no delay until imaging, it is recommended to investigate first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Australia, thromboembolism was the leading cause of direct maternal death in 2017-2018, accounting for 17 maternal deaths. Pregnancy is associated with a 4-5-fold increase in the risk of VTE compared to age-matched non-pregnant women due to the increase in venous stasis, procoagulants and the proinflammatory effect of pregnancy on vessel walls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Australia \u003Cstrong\u003EV/Q scan\u003C/strong\u003E is preferred if available, as recommended by the Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Both V/Q scan and \u003Cstrong\u003ECT Pulmonary Angiography\u003C/strong\u003E (CTPA) have a negative predictive value of 100%, however the sensitivity of CTPA in pregnancy is slightly reduced, specifically during the third-trimester. Additionally, V/Q scan has a lower frequency of inconclusive results (4% compared to 5.9%). If a V/Q scan is inconclusive, however, CTPA will need to be considered. There is a risk of fetal radiation with both CTPA and V/Q scan, and whilst the radiation dose is lower to the fetus in CTPA, the risk is considered negligible when compared to that of maternal PE. Additionally, there is an increased risk of maternal breast cancer from CTPA, especially when exposed during the third-trimester. Whilst the decision between V/Q scan and CTPA may not always be clear, an evaluation of typical physician practice found that 69% of investigators from PIOPEDII recommended V/Q Scan and 31% recommended CTPA, which is in line with the SOMANZ guidelines. It is important to note that if other pulmonary pathology is suspected, or there are significant abnormalities on a chest X-ray, V/Q scan is not preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this patient due to her known hypersensitivity reaction to iodine-containing contrast material. Even without this contraindication, V/Q scanning would still be preferred in pregnancy due to lower breast radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer\u003C/strong\u003E testing is not recommended in pregnancy as levels physiologically increase across all gestations and values can fluctuate by 50%. Additionally, a negative d-dimer in pregnancy does not rule out PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic dose rivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E and other direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated in pregnancy as they cross the placenta and their safety has not been established. They are also contraindicated during breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E would be the anticoagulant of choice if PE is confirmed, but investigation should precede treatment in this haemodynamically stable patient. Low molecular weight heparins are preferred in pregnancy as they do not cross the placenta. Postnatally, enoxaparin and warfarin are safe in breastfeeding and either can be used.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A V/Q scan is the preferred investigation for suspected pulmonary embolism in pregnancy.","D-dimer testing is not recommended if PE is suspected in pregnancy.","Direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated in pregnancy and breastfeeding."],"references":["Lowe S, Barrett H, Cutts B, Idel I, Laurie J, Makris A, Morton M, Said J. The SOMANZ Position Statement on Pulmonary Embolism in Pregnancy and Post-Partum. 2021 [Internet]. Available at: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2021/06/SOMANZ_PE_Guide_2021-Final-20210622.pdf","Mclintock, C, Brighton, T, Chunilal, S, Dekker, G, McDonnell, N, Mcrae, S, Muller, P, Tran, H, Walters, BNJ \u0026 Young, L 2011, \u2018Recommendations for the diagnosis and treatment of deep venous thrombosis and pulmonary embolism in pregnancy and the postpartum period\u2019,\u00a0Australian and New Zealand Journal of Obstetrics and Gynaecology,vol. 52, no. 1.","Hunt BJ, Parmar K, Horspool K, et al. The DiPEP (Diagnosis of PE in Pregnancy) biomarker study: An observational cohort study augmented with additional cases to determine the diagnostic utility of biomarkers for suspected venous thromboembolism during pregnancy and puerperium.\u00a0Br J Haematol. 2018;180(5):694\u2010704. doi:10.1111/bjh.15102","van der Pol LM, Tromeur C, Bistervels IM, et al. Pregnancy-Adapted YEARS Algorithm for Diagnosis of Suspected Pulmonary Embolism.\u00a0N Engl J Med. 2019;380(12):1139\u20101149. doi:10.1056/NEJMoa1813865","South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline 2020,\u00a0Thromboprophylaxis and Thromboembolic Disease in Pregnancy, Department of Health and Aging, Adelaide, viewed 7/8/2020, \u003Chttps://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/a070e7804eedf080b699b76a7ac0d6e4/Thromboprophylaxis+and+Thromboembolic+Disease+in+Pregnancy_PPG_v4_1_14052018.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-a070e7804eedf080b699b76a7ac0d6e4-n5ifkRg\u003E.","Stein PD, Woodard PK, Weg JG, Wakefield TW, Tapson VF, Sostman HD, Sos TA, Quinn DA, Leeper KV Jr, Hull RD, Hales CA, Gottschalk A, Goodman LR, Fowler SE, Buckley JD; PIOPED II investigators. Diagnostic pathways in acute pulmonary embolism: recommendations of the PIOPED II investigators. Am J Med. 2006 Dec;119(12):1048-55. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2006.05.060. PMID: 17145249."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2021"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T16:48:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T16:50:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2021"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114342"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\